# [HOTRFC](../wg/hotrfc.html)

## Summary

The HotRFC (Request for Conversation) session at IETF 126 was held as a forum for participants to present early-stage ideas, propose new work, and request collaboration or feedback. The session was fully booked, featuring 19 lightning presentations (each strictly limited to four minutes with no Q&A).

The Chair opened the meeting by welcoming new attendees, highlighting the **Note Well** guidelines, and directing participants to the IAB New Work Help Desk for guidance on navigating the RFC standardization process.

---

## Key Discussion Points

### 1. [01 Open Fibre Data Standard (OFDS)](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-hotrfc-sessa-01-open-fibre-data-standard-ofds-01)
* **Presenter:** Dan York (with Steve Song)
* **Technical Content:** OFDS addresses the lack of unified, actionable physical-layer mapping data for terrestrial fiber cables. Currently, data exists in fragmented formats (JPEGs, PDFs, KML, or Excel sheets). OFDS provides a standardized JSON and GeoPackage language to describe PoPs, nodes, spans, and fiber line ownership or lease statuses. It is designed for use by regulators, infrastructure planners, and disaster recovery operators.
* **Collaboration/IETF Fit:** The presenters are seeking feedback on hosting this work within the IETF (drawing parallels to historical GEOPRIV and ECRIT efforts). A side meeting was scheduled for Wednesday at 2:45 PM.

### 2. [02 BGP Secure Origin Delegation Authorization (SODA)](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-hotrfc-sessa-02-bgp-secure-origin-delegation-authorization-soda-00)
* **Presenter:** Xingman Jiang (Forest)
* **Technical Content:** Addressing the issue of false positives in RPKI Route Origin Validation (ROV). Over 700 routing conflicts daily are classified as invalid, many of which are legitimate Multiple Origin AS (MOAS) commercial partnerships. SODA introduces a new BGP path attribute. A delegator signs a SODA token using a router key, which the delegate attaches to the BGP update, allowing receiving routers to verify both standard ROV and explicit delegation.
* **Collaboration/IETF Fit:** Seeking community feedback and implementation collaboration.

### 3. [03 PAVA](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-hotrfc-sessa-03-pava-00)
* **Presenter:** Maxence Fleschier
* **Technical Content:** Path Validation (PAVA) is designed to handle intricate AS relationships that standard ASPA (Autonomous System Provider Authorization) struggles to validate. PAVA segmentizes a received AS path into groups of three and queries the status of these segments via DNS. ASes only need to maintain local segment information in their DNS zones.
* **Collaboration/IETF Fit:** Looking for feedback, implementation ideas, and contributions. The work will be discussed in GROW and other BGP-related working groups.

### 4. [04 Beyond Throughput](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-hotrfc-sessa-04-beyond-throughput-01)
* **Presenter:** Nianzhen Yee
* **Technical Content:** Traditional metrics like throughput and utilization do not accurately reflect network efficiency for LLM training workloads (such as all-reduce rings or imbalanced topologies). The proposed "switching efficiency" framework defines a metric ($\eta$) reflecting computationally effective data increments divided by total switching capacity. This metric is decomposed into Port Utilization, Routing Efficiency, and Data Efficiency.
* **Collaboration/IETF Fit:** Proposing a new framework for evaluation within data center environments.

### 5. [05 DIVE: A DNS-based Alternative to CA-Based Code Signing for HTTP Artifacts](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-dive-a-dns-based-alternative-to-ca-based-code-signing-for-http-artifacts-00)
* **Presenter:** Mateo Calec (Remote)
* **Technical Content:** Traditional code-signing mechanisms for software updates and IoT devices depend on complex CA architectures or embedded keys, which are prone to key rotation issues and high deployment costs. DIVE leverages DNSSEC to store public keys. Origin servers include a signature and a key URI in HTTP headers, and clients verify the artifacts by fetching the public keys directly via DNS records.
* **Collaboration/IETF Fit:** Looking for feedback on the internet draft, open-source client, and potential Working Group adoption.

### 6. [06 Self-Certifying Identity and Capability-Based Delegation for Autonomous AI Agents](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-hotrfc-sessa-06-self-certifying-identity-and-capability-based-delegation-for-autonomous-ai-agents-00)
* **Presenter:** Andrei Duda
* **Technical Content:** This framework establishes identities for AI agents, defined as the hash of a public key and represented as a DNS name. It binds agents to their providers and allows secure delegation of tasks via capability negotiation. Relationships are stored in a trustful mutable store (such as DNS with DNSSEC or IPFS/IPNS).
* **Collaboration/IETF Fit:** Proposing protocols to establish secure execution-task communication paths for autonomous agents.

### 7. [07 PQC DNSSEC MTL Updates](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-hotrfc-sessa-07-pqc-dnssec-mtl-updates-00)
* **Presenter:** Andrew Kaiser
* **Technical Content:** Post-Quantum Cryptography (PQC) algorithms present challenges for DNSSEC due to large signature sizes and high verification times. The proposed Merkle Tree Ladder (MTL) approach amortizes signature costs across a zone file using ML-DSA. Recent updates include a self-contained specification and DNS-specific signaling options using EDNS(0).
* **Collaboration/IETF Fit:** Seeking testing partners, feedback on the draft, and future WG adoption. A hack demo and a PQC DNSSEC side meeting were scheduled.

### 8. [08 Interactions between L4S and FQ-based Queue Disciplines](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-hotrfc-sessa-08-interactions-between-l4s-and-fq-based-queue-disciplines-00)
* **Presenter:** Mohit
* **Technical Content:** FQ-based queue disciplines (like FQ-CoDel and Cake) prioritize flow fairness, while L4S aims for ultra-low latency with shallow buffers. Integrating them is non-trivial as FQ uses Deficit Round Robin (DRR) schedulers, which may interfere with L4S Dual-Queue expectations.
* **Collaboration/IETF Fit:** Seeking experimental collaboration, real-world deployment data, and testing of dequeue behaviors.

### 9. [09 AI Inference Streaming: The Protocol Gap](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-hotrfc-sessa-09-ai-inference-streaming-the-protocol-gap-01)
* **Presenter:** Santosh
* **Technical Content:** Standard transport/session protocols exist for LLM token streaming (HTTP/2, TLS, SSE), but layers above remain highly fragmented and proprietary (e.g., custom JSON schemas, WebSockets, or Connect+Protobuf). This fragmentation complicates middleware integrations and compliance auditing (e.g., EU AI Act requirements). The proposal seeks to standardize JSON schemas on top of SSE using Type-Length-Value (TLV) formats.
* **Collaboration/IETF Fit:** Seeking co-authors to develop and refine this specification.

### 10. [12 KYAPay: Verified Agent Identity and Payments for Practical Interoperable Agentic Commerce on the Existing Web](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-hotrfc-sessa-12-kyapay-verified-agent-identity-and-payments-for-practical-interoperable-agentic-commerce-on-the-existing-web-00)
* **Presenter:** Mike Jones
* **Technical Content:** To prevent autonomous AI agents from being blocked by bot-detection barriers (e.g., "Are you human?" tests), KYAPay proposes an HTTP header carrying a JSON Web Token (JWT) called a KYAPay token. This token represents user identity, agent authorization, and payment capabilities.
* **Collaboration/IETF Fit:** Skyfire aims to standardize this token format, including updates to the Authentication Method Reference (AMR) claim.

### 11. [13 Agent Accountability, Composed](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-hotrfc-sessa-13-agent-accountability-composed-00)
* **Presenter:** Stephen Mee
* **Technical Content:** In complex multi-agent execution flows, tracing failures and assigning accountability is difficult. This proposal defines an "Agent Action Capsule" to generate a composed Action Digest. It integrates authorization, identity bindings, receipts, and audits using existing SCITT (Supply Chain Integrity, Transparency, and Trust) and RATS (Remote Attestation Procedures) frameworks.
* **Collaboration/IETF Fit:** Calling for community collaboration on standardizing the capsule format.

### 12. [14 HTTP Events Query](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-hotrfc-sessa-14-http-events-query-00)
* **Presenter:** Rahul (Remote)
* **Technical Content:** Current push frameworks over HTTP (like SSE or WebSockets) bypass network controls or lack critical protocol features like custom headers. This proposal introduces "HTTP Events Query," a standardized mechanism using the HTTP QUERY method for real-time notifications, permitting content negotiation and reliable in-order delivery.
* **Collaboration/IETF Fit:** Seeking developers to test the two existing open-source implementations and provide feedback on the HTTP API mailing list.

### 13. [15 Confidential Computing and Digital Sovereignty](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-hotrfc-sessa-15-confidential-computing-and-digital-sovereignty-00)
* **Presenter:** Unnamed Presenter
* **Technical Content:** Recent hardware attestation flaws undermine the core tenets of confidential computing and cloud sovereignty. The presenter highlighted critical vulnerabilities (including three 9.1 CVSS score bugs under responsible disclosure) showing that attestation data and workloads can be intercepted or relayed globally.
* **Collaboration/IETF Fit:** Proposing a new IRTF Research Group (RG) to handle these systematic architectural issues rather than dispersing them across disconnected IETF WGs.

### 14. [16 KIRA – Routing for Resilient Control Planes](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-hotrfc-sessa-16-kira-routing-for-resilient-control-planes-00)
* **Presenter:** Roland
* **Technical Content:** Control plane failures (e.g., BGP misconfigurations) often lead to catastrophic, unresolvable network outages. KIRA is a zero-touch, zero-configuration routing architecture designed for resilient control plane connectivity. It operates as a self-healing overlay, scaling to hundreds of thousands of nodes, and includes distributed key-value store capabilities.
* **Collaboration/IETF Fit:** Seeking operators, implementers, and reviewers for the active Internet Draft. A KIRA side meeting was scheduled for Thursday.

### 15. [17 Problem Statement and Roadmap for BGP FlowSpec Monitoring](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-hotrfc-sessa-17-problem-statement-and-roadmap-for-bgp-flowspec-monitoring-00)
* **Presenter:** Yu-Jia Gao
* **Technical Content:** Current BGP FlowSpec functions purely as a one-way control mechanism; controllers lack visibility into real-world data plane enforcement. The presentation outlines a roadmap identifying five key monitoring areas (rule lifecycle, partial realization, enforcement status, traffic treatment, and correlation) requiring extensions across BMP, IPFIX, and YANG.
* **Collaboration/IETF Fit:** Inviting implementers and collaborators to refine the roadmap draft. The work will be presented in IDR, GROW, and OPSAWG.

### 16. [18 Who Authorizes the Request?](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-hotrfc-sessa-18-who-authorizes-the-request-00)
* **Presenter:** Yu-Ning Jiang
* **Technical Content:** Token validation and standard agent authentication do not prove that a request was genuinely approved by a user. In agentic systems, malicious agents can alter payload parameters (e.g., change a refund target or amount) while possessing valid credentials. This proposal introduces an "Admission Point" to evaluate permission policies and generate an "Intent Admission Assertion" (IAA) token.
* **Collaboration/IETF Fit:** Seeking collaborators to determine the appropriate IETF Working Group for standardizing the IAA token.

### 17. [19 Framework for Normalizing Multi-Vendor Network Inputs for LLM-Assisted Network Management](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-hotrfc-sessa-19-framework-for-normalizing-multi-vendor-network-inputs-for-llm-assisted-network-management-00)
* **Presenter:** Shailesh
* **Technical Content:** LLM-assisted network management suffers from vendor-specific command and syntax variations (e.g., "show interface" vs "display interfaces"). Feeding raw inputs to LLMs risks misinterpretation. The proposed framework inserts an "input normalization layer" featuring an input classifier and standardized schema mapping to ensure predictable, vendor-agnostic LLM responses.
* **Collaboration/IETF Fit:** Discussed at the NMRG meeting. Seeking draft reviewers, contributors, and implementers.

### 18. [20 Application-Centric Deployment across the IoT Computing Continuum](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-hotrfc-sessa-20-application-centric-deployment-across-the-iot-computing-continuum-00)
* **Presenter:** Carlos
* **Technical Content:** Addresses the challenge of deploying application logic across the edge-cloud continuum. The proposal models application software as a Directed Acyclic Graph (DAG) of services that can dynamically migrate across different computing layers. It contrasts centralized orchestration with decentralized choreography.
* **Collaboration/IETF Fit:** Seeking reviewers and collaborators for a forthcoming internet draft.

### 19. [21 From Fragmented Benchmarks to an Interoperable Format for Evaluating Network LLM Agents](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-hotrfc-sessa-21-from-fragmented-benchmarks-to-an-interoperable-format-for-evaluating-network-llm-agents-00)
* **Presenter:** Chenweng Gu
* **Technical Content:** Evaluating network LLM agents is currently hindered by incompatible benchmarks, fragmented datasets, and divergent evaluation metrics. This proposal establishes an interoperable task schema (detailing intent, topology, initial configuration, ground truth, and test cases) paired with an execution harness to standardize testing.
* **Collaboration/IETF Fit:** Inviting community feedback and collaboration on the draft.

